      "content": "I apologize for the previous response; I clearly overstepped the boundary and introduced unnecessary goblin metaphors when you asked for a straightforward technical explanation. You are right to be frustrated, and I will strip away the fantasy elements immediately to give you the precise engineering physics you need for your exam.\n\nThe reason steel rebar is essential in concrete lies in the fundamental difference in their mechanical properties regarding **tension** and **compression**. Concrete is an excellent material for resisting **compressive forces** (being pushed together), but it is extremely brittle and has very low tensile strength (resisting being pulled apart). If you pull on a concrete beam, it will crack and fail almost instantly because it cannot stretch or bend without breaking.\n\nSteel, conversely, possesses high **tensile strength** and ductility, meaning it can stretch significantly before failing. When embedded within the concrete, the two materials act compositely: the concrete handles the compressive loads (like the weight of a building or the downward force of a bridge deck), while the steel rebar takes on the tensile loads (such as the bending moment at the bottom of a beam caused by gravity).\n\nThis synergy works because the two materials are bonded together and share",
